<Post
  title="Dato vs Mou Sugu: Menu Bar Calendar Apps for Mac Compared"
  description="Dato is a powerful $16 menu bar calendar with world clocks and reminders. Mou Sugu is a free, focused meeting countdown. Which approach suits your Mac?"
  path="/blog/dato-alternative"
  h1="Dato vs Mou Sugu: power tool or pocket knife?"
  datePublished="2026-07-15"
>
  <p class="lede">
    <a href="https://sindresorhus.com/dato">Dato</a> is the Swiss-army knife of menu bar
    calendars. Mou Sugu is a single sharp blade. Both are good — for different hands.
  </p>

  <p>
    Dato, by the prolific Sindre Sorhus, packs a remarkable amount into the menu bar: a calendar
    with week numbers, upcoming events, <strong>world clocks</strong> with offline city search,
    Apple Reminders support, fullscreen meeting notifications, global keyboard shortcuts, and a
    deep customization surface. It costs <strong>$16 one-time</strong> on the Mac App Store — no
    subscription, free upgrades.
  </p>

  <p>
    Mou Sugu does one thing: it shows <strong>how long until your next meeting</strong> —
    <code>in 12m: Standup</code> — and gives you the Join button for Zoom, Google Meet, Teams,
    or Webex. It is free, open source, and has almost nothing to configure.
  </p>

  <h2>Side by side</h2>
  <div class="table-scroll">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Dato</th><th>Mou Sugu</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Price</td><td>$16 one-time (Mac App Store)</td><td>Free, open source (MIT)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Scope</td><td>Calendar + world clocks + reminders + notifications</td><td>Meeting countdown + one-click join</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Menu bar countdown</td><td>Upcoming event display, configurable</td><td>Live countdown with event title, updates every minute</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Join meetings</td><td>Yes — from notification, shortcut, or event details</td><td>Yes — Join in the bar, Rejoin if you drop mid-call</td></tr>
        <tr><td>World clocks / time zones</td><td>Yes, a highlight feature</td><td>—</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Apple Reminders</td><td>Yes</td><td>—</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Customization</td><td>Very deep</td><td>Deliberately minimal</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Source code</td><td>Closed</td><td>Open (GitHub)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Languages</td><td>Multiple</td><td>English and Spanish</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2>Choose Dato if…</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>You work across time zones and want world clocks next to your calendar.</li>
    <li>You live in Apple Reminders and want them in the same menu.</li>
    <li>You enjoy tailoring every detail, and $16 for a polished tool is fair (it is).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Choose Mou Sugu if…</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>What you actually need is the countdown to your next call, nothing else.</li>
    <li>You prefer free and open source, with the code one click away.</li>
    <li>You want zero setup: grant calendar access and you are done.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If Dato's feature list makes you nod, buy it — it is well built and fairly priced. If it
    makes you tired, Mou Sugu is the two-minute alternative.
  </p>
</Post>
